    "A trusting relationship between the healthcare staff and patients is often perceived to require human input [15].",
    "Robotic applications designed to work in specific settings with limited interaction with people (e.g., service robots) are often received positively, and are perceived as being less difficult to implement than those that were designed to operate in human-dense surroundings [15].",
    "Robotic applications designed to support healthcare staff and do not replace them receive higher levels of acceptance [16].The next barriers are related to cost.",
    "Commercially available robots are few and expensive, limiting their usability to organisation with significant purchasing power.",
    "As the technology matures, it is expected that an increase in demand may cause a decline in direct costs."
